The Hydrological Cycle

The hydrological cycle (also called the water cycle) describes the continuous movement of water through the Earthâs systemsâocean, land, atmosphere, and biosphere. This process is essential to life on Earth and plays a central role in shaping geological features, particularly streams and rivers.

The Water Cycle

The various components of the water cycle. Black or white text indicates the movement or transfer of water from one reservoir to another. Yellow text indicates the storage of water. Source: Steven, E. (2015)

  • Water is constantly cycling, even if most of it remains in the ocean.
  • Streams are a small but critical component of this cycle.
  • Even tiny percentages (like 0.03% in rivers/lakes) play a vital role in shaping Earthâs surface and supporting life.
  • Understanding residence time helps us model climate, predict droughts, and manage water resources.

Processes in the Water Cycle

The movement of water between reservoirs is driven by solar energy and gravity through the following processes:

Process Description
Evaporation Water changes from liquid to gas, mostly from oceans and lakes.
Transpiration Water is released from plant leaves into the atmosphere.
Precipitation Water vapor condenses and falls as rain or snow.
Infiltration Water seeps into the ground to become part of the groundwater system.
Runoff Water moves over the land surface into streams and rivers.
Groundwater flow Water slowly moves through subsurface materials back into streams or oceans.

Residence Time of Water

Residence time refers to the average amount of time water spends in a given reservoir.

Reservoir Estimated Residence Time
Atmosphere ~8.2 days
Oceans ~850,000 years
Glaciers Hundreds to thousands of years
Groundwater Days to millennia (depends on depth)
Lakes Days to decades
Rivers Days to weeks

Drainage Basins

A drainage basin (also called a watershed) is the land area from which all precipitation collects and flows into a particular stream or river. It includes all surface water from rain, snowmelt, and nearby streams that drain into the main stream channel. A stream is any body of flowing water, regardless of size.

Definitions - Drainage Basins

  • Stream: A channel of flowing water, from small creeks to large rivers.
  • Drainage Basin: The area of land where precipitation collects and drains into a stream.
  • Drainage Divide: The boundary between two drainage basins, typically marked by a ridge or high point of land.

Types of Drainage Patterns

Typical dendritic, trellis, and rectangular stream drainage patterns. Source: Steven, E. (2015)

Left: a typical deranged pattern; right: a typical radial drainage pattern developed around a mountain or hill. Source: Steven, E. (2015)

The shape and structure of drainage networks vary depending on geology and topography.

Pattern Description Common Settings
Dendritic Tree-like branching; forms when rock is uniform and erodes equally in all directions Granite, gneiss, volcanic rocks
Trellis Parallel tributaries join at right angles; influenced by folded or tilted layers Folded sedimentary rocks, e.g., Rockies
Rectangular Streams follow jointed or faulted rock, forming right angles Fractured bedrock or fault zones
Deranged Irregular, chaotic patterns with many lakes and wetlands Glaciated terrain, Canadian Shield
Radial Streams radiate outward from a central high point Volcanic cones or domes

Graded vs.Â Ungraded Streams

The topographic profile of a typical graded stream. Source: Steven, E. (2015)

  • Graded Stream: A stream in dynamic equilibrium, with a smooth concave profile where erosion = deposition.
  • Ungraded Stream: Has irregular profile with steep drops, rapids, or waterfalls. Can become graded over time via erosion.

A stream may lose its graded profile due to tectonic uplift or a drop in base level (e.g., river incision after glaciation or dam construction).

Base Level and Stream Terraces

Terrace formation by incising or widening floodplains. Source: https://cfpub.epa.gov

Base Level

  • The lowest point a stream can erode to:
    • Ultimate base level = Sea level
    • Temporary base level = Lakes, larger rivers, or dams

Stream Terraces

  • Formed when a stream cuts down into its own floodplain.
  • Usually created due to:
    • A drop in base level
    • Decrease in sediment supply
    • Uplift of land

Cause Effect on Stream
Natural uplift Increases gradient â more erosion â rejuvenation of stream
Sea level drop Lowers base level â stream incises deeper into valley
Glacial rebound Raises land, creating new waterfalls or canyons
Dam construction Creates an artificial lake (reservoir) â raises local base level

The Davis Cycle of Erosion

A depiction of the Davis cycle of erosion: a: initial stage, b: youthful stage, c: mature stage, and d: old age. Source: Steven, E. (2015)

  • Proposed by geologist William Davis, this model describes how landscapes evolve over time through stream erosion.
Stage Description
Youthful Steep gradients, V-shaped valleys, waterfalls and rapids, active downcutting
Mature Wider valleys, reduced gradients, more lateral erosion, sediment deposition
Old Age Broad floodplains, meanders, low energy, extensive deposition

ï¸ Note: While the Davis model is simplified and predates plate tectonics, it remains useful for conceptualising stream evolution.

  • Streams shape landscapes over time through erosion and deposition.
  • Drainage patterns reflect underlying rock and tectonic history.
  • Streams evolve from steep, fast-flowing channels to low-gradient, meandering rivers.
  • Understanding stream behavior is essential for flood management, land planning, and environmental protection.

Stream Erosion and Deposition

Streams are powerful agents of erosion, transportation, and deposition. The movement of sediment and solutes in a stream is controlled by velocity, channel shape, and discharge volume. Understanding how sediment moves helps explain stream dynamics, floodplain development, and landscape evolution.

Velocity Distribution in Stream Channels

Stream velocity is not uniform:

  • Fastest Flow: Just below the surface, near the center of the channel.
  • Slowest Flow: Along the bottom and edges due to friction.
  • In Curves (Meanders):
    • Fastest on the outside bend â erosion.
    • Slowest on the inside bend â deposition.
Stream Condition Effect on Velocity
Smooth channel, high gradient High velocity
Rough bed or wide shallow channel Lower velocity due to friction
During flood (bank-full stage) Velocity increases significantly

Sediment Transport Types

Modes of transportation of sediments and dissolved ions (represented by red dots with + and â signs) in a stream. Source: Steven, E. (2015)

  • Stream sediments are transported in three main ways:
Transport Type Description
Bed Load Large particles (sand, gravel, cobbles) that roll, slide, or bounce (saltation) along the bed.
Suspended Load Finer particles (silt, clay) carried in suspension; influenced by turbulence.
Dissolved Load Soluble ions (e.g., CaÂ²âº, Clâ») transported invisibly in water.

The volume of each load type varies with stream velocity and sediment availability.

HjulstrÃ¶m-Sundborg Diagram

The HjulstrÃ¶m-Sundborg diagram showing the relationships between particle size and the tendency to be eroded, transported, or deposited at different current velocities. Source: Steven, E. (2015)

  • This table illustrates the relationship between stream velocity and particle size, showing when particles are eroded, transported, or deposited.
Particle Type Erosion and Transport Behavior
Fine sand (~0.2â0.5 mm) Easiest to erode compared to other grain sizes.
Very fine particles (clay, silt) Difficult to erode due to cohesion, but easy to keep suspended once in motion.
Larger particles (gravel, cobbles) Require high velocity to erode, but stay mobile once entrained in the flow.

Erosion requires higher velocity than transport or deposition.

#Natural LevÃ©es and Floodplain Processes

  • When streams flood:
    1. Water spills over the banks and spreads across the floodplain.
    2. Velocity drops suddenly due to increased channel width.
    3. Coarse sediment (sand, silt) is deposited along the edge of the channel.
    4. Finer particles (clay) travel farther before settling.

Formation of Natural LevÃ©es

The development of natural levÃ©es during flooding of a stream. The sediments of the levÃ©e become increasingly fine away from the stream channel, and even finer sedimentsâclay, silt, and fine sandâare deposited across most of the flood plain. Source: Steven, E. (2015)

Process Result
Flood overtops banks Sediment drops quickly
Repeated flooding Builds up raised banks = levÃ©es
Beyond levÃ©es Floodplain with finer sediments

These natural embankments can help contain future floodsâuntil overtopped.

Stream Types

Stream channels vary in shape, energy, and sediment transport depending on their gradient, geology, sediment supply, and stage of landscape evolution. Understanding different stream types helps us interpret river systems and their associated landforms.

Characteristics of Stream Types

Stream Type Key Characteristics
Youthful Streams - Steep gradients
- Narrow, V-shaped valleys
- High erosion rates
- Features like rapids, waterfalls, step-pool morphology
Braided Streams - Multiple shallow channels separated by bars
- High sediment load
- Often found in glacial valleys or volcanic regions
Meandering Streams - Single, sinuous channel
- Low gradient, broad floodplain
- Erosion on outer bends and deposition on inner bends

Step-Pool Morphology and Sediment Dynamics

Step-Pool Morphology

  • Common in youthful, steep streams.
  • Stream alternates between:
    • Pools: Deep, slow-moving water sections.
    • Steps: Short, turbulent drops, often over large boulders or bedrock.

Function:

  • Step-pool structures dissipate stream energy, reducing erosion and promoting sediment sorting.

Sediment Dynamics

Sediment Process Description
Bed Load Transport Large particles (gravel, cobbles) bounce or roll along the stream bed (traction, saltation).
Suspended Load Fine sediments (silt, clay) carried within the water column.
Channel Changes During high flow (floods), streams erode banks, deposit sediments, and shift positions.
  • In braided streams, sediment supply exceeds transport capacity, causing frequent channel shifts.
  • In meandering streams, erosion dominates on the outer bend (cut bank) and deposition on the inner bend (point bar).

Deltas and Their Formation at River Mouths

Delta Formation

  • A delta forms where a stream enters a standing body of water (lake, sea) and deposits sediment.
  • Stream velocity drops suddenly â sediments settle out.
Delta Characteristics Description
Coarse material deposits near river mouth Sand, gravel form topset beds.
Fine material carried farther Silt, clay form foreset and bottomset beds.
Delta Progradation Deltas build outward into the water body over time.

Flooding

  • Flooding occurs when a streamâs discharge exceeds the capacity of its channel, causing water to spill onto the surrounding floodplain. Floods shape landscapes, enrich soils, but also threaten human settlements.

  • Understanding the seasonal patterns of stream discharge and historic flood events helps in planning and mitigation strategies.

Seasonal Stream Discharge Patterns

Region Discharge Pattern
Continental Canada Highest discharge in late spring and early summer due to snowmelt.
Coastal British Columbia Highest discharge in winter from rainfall; lower seasonal snow influence.

Flood Prevention Strategies

Strategy Purpose
Floodplain Zoning Restricts building in flood-prone areas to minimize risk.
Dyking Builds levees or embankments to contain floodwaters.
Monitoring Tracks snowpack, precipitation, and stream discharge.
Emergency Planning Prepares evacuation routes, warnings, and response plans.
Public Education Informs citizens about risks and safe actions during floods.
